ism, 1941–1983 -- tIntroduction -- tFrederic H. Douglas and René D'Harnoncourt: Indian Art of the United States, 1941 -- tHenry Moore: Primitive Art, 1941 -- tAdolph Gottlieb and Mark Rothko: The Portrait and the Modern Artist, 1943 -- tRalph Linton and Paul S.Wingert: Arts of the South Seas, 1946 -- tBarnett Newman: Art of the South Seas, 1946 -- tBarnett Newman: Northwest Coast Indian Painting, 1946 -- tD. H. Kahnweiler: Negro Art and Cubism, 1948 -- tJean Dubuffet: Anticultural Positions, 1951 -- tJean Laude: French Painting and Negro Art, 1968 -- tPart IV: The Museum of Modern Art's 1984: Primitivism Exhibition and Its Aftermath -- tIntroduction -- tWilliam Rubin: Modernist Primitivism, 1984 -- tThomas McEvilley: Doctor, Lawyer, Indian Chief, 1984 -- tJames Clifford: Histories of the Tribal and the Modern, 1985 -- tKirkvarnedoe: On the Claims and Critics of the "Primitivism" Show, 1985 -- tHal Foster: The "Primitive" Unconscious of Modern Art, 1985 -- tThomas McEvilley: The Global Issue, 1990 -- tLucy Lippard: Naming, 1990 -- tSieglinde Lemke: Primitivist Modernism, 1998 -- tCoda: Quotations from Artists and Writers -- tChronology of Events, Exhibitions, and Publications -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the first to bring together texts documenting the encounter between Western artists and writers and what has historically been called primitive art—the traditional, indigenous arts of Africa, Oceania, and North America. Beginning with the "discovery" of that art by European artists and writers early in the twentieth century, this anthology charts the evolving pictorial responses, artistic aspirations, aesthetic theories, and cultural debates that have developed from this encounter. Written by artists, literary figures, collectors, museum curators, and cultural critics, these essays—most of them never before translated or reprinted—show the dazzling range of issues elicited by the confrontation with primitive arts and cultures. Primitivism designates not a specific movement or group of artists, but a persuasive notion crucial to twentieth-century art and modern thinking generally. Because the encounter between the West and primitive art took place at the height of Western colonialism, a number of racial and political issues come into play, either overtly or implicitly, in writings about both the art and the people who produced it. The contributions to this volume speak to each other in provocative ways, giving a unique overview of those issues. Jack Flam provides an introduction to the book and brief outlines for each of its four sections. Also included are a coda of "ations from artists and critics from throughout the century; a chronology of events, exhibitions, and publications; an extensive bibliography; and over forty illustrations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Prehistoric. 0aArt. 0aPrimitivism in art. 4aArt. 4aEuropean. 7aART / European.2bisacsh1 aDeutch, Miriam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlam, Jack, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021503040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093517440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935174423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935174/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles